which he &s;till thought had been created by
the intrigues and machinations of Lady
Ca&s;tlenorth.</P>
<P>In art, however, &s;he was &s;o much his
&s;uperior, that the very means he adopted
to obtain &s;atisfaction, was, in her hands, a
