of which the very &s;u&s;picion threw him into
agonies at the very moment his rea&s;on
told him that he ought not to think of her
for him&s;elf. Jealou&s;y now added to the
pangs of di&s;appointed love, and the letter
which Cele&s;tina had endeavoured to word
&s;o as to calm and &s;ooth him, and to teach
him to &s;ubmit to that nece&s;&s;ity of which he
allowed the force, &s;eemed to him to
