avoided, to name Cele&s;tina, and to expre&s;s
her &s;atisfaction that &s;he was likely to be &s;o
well married. "After all the conver&s;ation
there has been about this young per&s;on,"
&s;aid &s;he, affecting to have a great deal of
feeling for her, "I am very glad that the
poor girl will be &s;o well e&s;tabli&s;hed. A man
of Vava&s;our's independent fortune can well
