&s;o&s;ten her voice, her piercing and en|quiring
eyes were demanding from the
countenance of Willoughby that explana|tion
which &s;he knew it would give of his
real &s;entiments; and &s;he &s;aw the blood for|&s;ake
his cheeks, his lips turn white and
tremble, and a mingled expre&s;&s;ion of doubt,
<PB N="220" REF="230">
fear, anger, and di&s;dain, marked on his fea|tures.
"If I were certain, Madam," &s;aid
