if you plea&s;ed."</P>
<P>"I thank you, Sir," replied Willough|by,
who &s;aw whither the di&s;cour&s;e would
tend; "but tho&s;e matters are the lea&s;t of
my concern."</P>
<P>"Stay, however, one day," &s;aid Lord
Ca&s;tlenorth, "that you may execute &s;ome
bu&s;ine&s;s for me. Surely, nephew, you will
oblige me &s;o far."</P>
<P>Though every hour's delay was death to
him, he at length agreed, on his uncle's
repeated entreaties, to &s;tay four and twenty
hours longer at Naples; and then leaving
the room, he was followed by the officious
Mrs. Calder, who de&s;iring leave to &s;ay half
<PB N="225" REF="235">
a dozen words to him alone, he &s;uffered
